{
  "text": "The prevalence of DDDIs (5.9%) falls between the lowest and highest rates presented in earlier studies (0.7-16%). [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Two of these studies have used exactly the same criteria (SFINX) for DDDIs, [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] and showed strikingly similar prevalence rates of 5% and 4.8%. Johnell and Klarin's was a register-based study in a general older population whereas the study of HosiaRandell et al. was performed in an institutional setting. That study showed that the most common DDDIs were related to the use of potassium-sparing diuretics, carbamazepine, and codeine. Compared with residents not exposed to DDDIs, those exposed to potential DDDIs were more likely to be younger, to have a prior history of stroke, to be taking psychotropics, to be administered nine or more drugs daily and to be taking potentially inappropriate drugs. [CITATION_8] Our results are in line with earlier studies concluding that a higher number of prescribed drugs increases the risk of DDDIs. [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] Most studies have assessed DDDIs but not their outcomes. Only a few studies have explored the adverse events as consequences of DDDIs. [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] To our knowledge, our study is the first one to investigate the association between DDDIs and mortality. It is somewhat surprising that no association was observed. Even though mortality is high in a study population like ours, our study is underpowered to detect small differences in mortality between those with DDDIs and those without.",
  "correct_citation": {
